SIMPLE: gill
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gill
<hw>Gill</hw> <pr>(g⟦icr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Dan.
<ets>gi⟦ae⟧lle</ets>, <ets>gelle</ets>; akin to Sw. <ets>g⟦aum⟧l</ets>,
Icel. <ets>gj⟦oum⟧lnar</ets> gills; cf. AS. <ets>geagl</ets>,
<ets>geahl</ets>, jaw.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>An
organ for aquatic respiration; a branchia.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fishes perform respiration under water by the
<qex>gills</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Gills</xex> are usually lamellar or filamentous
appendages, through which the blood circulates, and in which it is
exposed to the action of the air contained in the water. In vertebrates
they are appendages of the visceral arches on either side of the neck.
In invertebrates they occupy various situations.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The radiating,
gill-shaped plates forming the under surface of a mushroom.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The fleshy flap that hangs below
the beak of a fowl; a wattle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The flesh under or about the chin.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Spinning)</fld> <def>One of the combs of closely
ranged steel pins which divide the ribbons of flax fiber or wool into
fewer parallel filaments.</def> <ety>[Prob. so called from F.
<ets>aiguilles</ets>, needles. <au>Ure.</au>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Gill arches</b></col>, <col><b>Gill
bars</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <cd>Same as <cref>Branchial
arches</cref>.</cd> -- <col><b>Gill clefts</b></col>. <fld>(Anat.)</fld>
<cd>Same as <cref>Branchial clefts</cref>. See under
<er>Branchial</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Gill cover</b></col>,
<col><b>Gill lid</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See <er>Operculum</er>.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Gill frame</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Gill
head</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Flax Manuf.)</fld>, <cd>a spreader; a
machine for subjecting flax to the action of gills.</cd>
<au>Knight.</au> -- <col><b>Gill net</b></col>, <cd>a flat net so
suspended in the water that its meshes allow the heads of fish to pass,
but catch in the gills when they seek to extricate themselves.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Gill opening</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Gill
slit</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>an opening behind and
below the head of most fishes, and some amphibians, by which the water
from the gills is discharged. In most fishes there is a single opening
on each side, but in the sharks and rays there are five, or more, on
each side.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Gill rakes</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Gill rakers</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>horny
filaments, or progresses, on the inside of the branchial arches of
fishes, which help to prevent solid substances from being carried into
gill cavities.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gill
<hw>Gill</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <def>A
two-wheeled frame for transporting timber.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gill
<hw>Gill</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A leech.</def> <altsp>[Also
<asp>gell</asp>.]</altsp> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>
<rj><au>Jameison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Gill
<hw>Gill</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>gil</ets>.]</ety> <def>A
woody glen; a narrow valley containing a stream.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.
& Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Gill
<hw>Gill</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>gille</ets>,
<ets>gelle</ets>, a sort of measure for wine, LL. <ets>gillo</ets>,
<ets>gello</ets>., Cf. <er>Gallon</er>.]</ety> <def>A measure of
capacity, containing one fourth of a pint.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Gill
<hw>Gill</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. from
<ets>Gillian</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A young woman; a sweetheart;
a flirting or wanton girl.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Each Jack with his
<xex>Gill</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The ground ivy (<spn>Nepeta
Glechoma</spn>); -- called also <altname>gill over the ground</altname>,
and other like names.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Malt liquor medicated with ground ivy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gill ale</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Ale flavored with
ground ivy.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>
<cd>Alehoof.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>gilled</ent>⟦br⟧
